"Almeida J., Achten W.M.J., Duarte M.P., Mendes B.M., Muys B.M.","Benchmarking the environmental performance of the jatropha biodiesel system through a generic life cycle assessment",2011,"Environmental Science and Technology","45","12",,"5447","5453",,,10.1021/es200257m,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79959196086&partnerID=40&md5=65b298e1d163795fc090f28a164515f3","Division Forest, Nature and Landscape, Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, Celestijnenlaan 200 e Box 2411, BE-3001 Leuven, Belgium; UBIA, Grupo de Disciplinas da Ecologia da Hidrosfera, Faculdade de Ciências e Tecnologia, Universidade Nova de Lisboa, 2829-516 Caparica, Portugal","Almeida, J., Division Forest, Nature and Landscape, Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, Celestijnenlaan 200 e Box 2411, BE-3001 Leuven, Belgium; Achten, W.M.J., Division Forest, Nature and Landscape, Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, Celestijnenlaan 200 e Box 2411, BE-3001 Leuven, Belgium; Duarte, M.P., UBIA, Grupo de Disciplinas da Ecologia da Hidrosfera, Faculdade de Ciências e Tecnologia, Universidade Nova de Lisboa, 2829-516 Caparica, Portugal; Mendes, B.M., UBIA, Grupo de Disciplinas da Ecologia da Hidrosfera, Faculdade de Ciências e Tecnologia, Universidade Nova de Lisboa, 2829-516 Caparica, Portugal; Muys, B.M., Division Forest, Nature and Landscape, Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, Celestijnenlaan 200 e Box 2411, BE-3001 Leuven, Belgium","In addition to available country or site-specific life cycle studies on Jatropha biodiesel we present a generic, location-independent life cycle assessment and provide a general but in-depth analysis of the environmental performance of Jatropha biodiesel for transportation. Additionally, we assess the influence of changes in byproduct use and production chain. In our assessments, we went beyond the impact on energy requirement and global warming by including impacts on ozone layer and terrestrial acidification and eutrophication. The basic Jatropha biodiesel system consumes eight times less nonrenewable energy than conventional diesel and reduces greenhouse gas emissions by 51%. This result coincides with the lower limit of the range of reduction percentages available in literature for this system and for other liquid biofuels. The impact on the ozone layer is also lower than that provoked by fossil diesel, although eutrophication and acidification increase eight times. This study investigates the general impact trends of the Jatropha system, although not considering land-use change. The results are useful as a benchmark against which other biodiesel systems can be evaluated, to calculate repayment times for land-use change induced carbon loss or as guideline with default values for assessing the environmental performance of specific variants of the system. © 2011 American Chemical Society.",,"Carbon loss; Default values; Energy requirements; Environmental performance; In-depth analysis; Jatropha; Land-use change; Life-cycle assessments; Liquid biofuels; Lower limits; Non-renewable energy; Production chain; Site-specific; Acidification; Biodiesel; Environmental management; Eutrophication; Forestry; Gas emissions; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Land use; Ozone; Ozone layer; Rating; Life cycle; biodiesel; acidification; benchmarking; biofuel; carbon balance; emission control; environmental impact assessment; eutrophication; global warming; land use change; life cycle analysis; ozone; performance assessment; shrub; vegetable oil; acidification; article; environmental impact assessment; eutrophication; greenhouse effect; Jatropha; life cycle assessment; ozone layer; quality control; Acids; Biofuels; Conservation of Energy Resources; Environment; Eutrophication; Global Warming; Jatropha; Ozone; Reference Standards; Thermodynamics; Jatropha",,"Acids; Biofuels; Ozone, 10028-15-6",,,,"Verrastro, F., Ladislaw, S., Providing energy security in an interdependent world (2007) The Washington Q., 30 (4), pp. 95-104; Cherubini, F., Bird, N., Cowie, A.